[[Withers Stakes]] (1987) | awards = | honours = | updated= }} '''Gone West''' (March 10, 1984 – September 7, 2009) was an American [[Thoroughbred]] [[Horse racing|racehorse]]. Bred by William O. Reed, he was a son of the influential sire [[Mr. Prospector]]. His dam, [[Secrettame]], was a daughter of 1973 [[United States Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|U.S. Triple Crown]] winner [[Secretariat (horse)|Secretariat]]. Purchased by [[Alice du Pont Mills]] and raced under her Hickory Tree Stable banner, Gone West was conditioned for racing by [[National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame|U.S. Racing Hall of Fame]] trainer [[Woody Stephens]]. While Gone West won three important stakes races, he is best known as a sire and a sire of sires. At [[Stud (horse)|stud]], among the notable horses he sired are: * [[West by West]] (1989-2011) - multiple stakes winner with career earnings of $1,038,123 * [[Zafonic]] (1990-2002) - won [[British Classic Races|British Classic]] [[2,000 Guineas Stakes]] [[Cartier Racing Award|European Champion Two-Year-Old Colt]] * [[Lassigny (horse)|Lassigny]] (b. 1991) - won G1 [[Canadian International Stakes|Rothman's International]] (1995), career earnings $1,318,371 * [[Da Hoss]] (b. 1992) - won [[Breeders' Cup Mile]] (1996, 1998), career earnings $1,931,558 * [[Elusive Quality]] (1993-2018) - stakes winner, sired [[Smarty Jones]], [[Raven's Pass]], [[Quality Road]] * [[Commendable]] (1997-2014) - won [[Belmont Stakes]] (2000) * [[Speightstown (horse)|Speightstown]] (b. 1998) - won [[Breeders' Cup Sprint]] (2004), [[American Champion Sprint Horse]] (2004), career earnings $1,258,256 * [[Came Home]] (1999-2021) - multiple Grade 1 winner, career earnings $1,835,940 * [[Johar]] (1999-2014) - won G1 [[Hollywood Derby]] (2002), G1 [[Breeders' Cup Turf]] (2003); career earnings $1,494,496 * [[Marsh Side]] (b. 2003) - won G1 [[Canadian International Stakes|Canadian International]], career earnings $1,519,706 Other sons of Gone West who became good sires were Zamindar, Mr. Greeley, Proud Citizen, [[Grand Slam (horse)|Grand Slam]], and Western Winter. Gone West is the damsire of 2005 [[Epsom Derby]] winner, [[Motivator (horse)|Motivator]]. At maturity, he reached {{hands|16}} high.{{cite news |author1=Anne Peters |title=Pedigree Analysis: Is Bigger Always Better? |url=http://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/90474/pedigree-analysis-is-bigger-always-better |access-date=19 November 2023 |work=Blood Horse |date=13 March 2015}} Gone West stood at Mill Ridge Farm in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. They announced that the stallion would be pensioned after the 2009 breeding season. However, he was euthanized due to complications from [[Horse colic|colic]]. ==References== {{Reflist}} ==External links== * [http://www.pedigreequery.com/gone+west Gone West's pedigree and partial racing stats] * [https://web.archive.org/web/20090511151010/http://www.millridge.com/stallions-gonewest.aspx Gone West at Mill Ridge Farm] [[Category:1984 racehorse births]] [[Category:2009 racehorse deaths]] [[Category:Racehorses bred in Kentucky]] [[Category:Racehorses trained in the United States]] [[Category:Thoroughbred family 2-f]] [[Category:Chefs-de-Race]]

{{Use American English|date=December 2019}} {{Use mdy dates|date=May 2021}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Gone West | image = Gone West Group Photo Canyons.jpg | image_size = | landscape = | alt = | caption = | origin = [[Nashville, Tennessee]] | genre = [[Country pop]], [[folk-pop]] | years_active = 2018–2020 | label = [[Triple Tigers]] | past_members = * [[Colbie Caillat]] * Nelly Joy * [[Jason Reeves (songwriter)|Jason Reeves]] * [[Justin Young (singer, born 1978)|Justin Kawika Young]] | website = }} '''Gone West''' was an American [[country pop]] group composed of [[Colbie Caillat]], [[Justin Young (singer, born 1978)|Justin Young]], [[Jason Reeves (songwriter)|Jason Reeves]], and Nelly Joy. They made their debut as a band on the Grand Ole Opry stage{{Cite web|date=October 25, 2018|title=Colbie Caillat to Debut New Band Gone West at Opry Goes Pink|url=https://countrymusictattletale.com/2018/10/25/colbie-caillat-to-debut-new-band-gone-west-at-opry-goes-pink/|access-date=June 23, 2020|website=Country Music Tattle Tale - Your country music news source|language=en-US}} and signed with [[Triple Tigers]].{{Cite web|date=January 18, 2019|title=Triple Tigers Records Signs Gone West For Debut EP, 'Tides' Out Today|url=https://musicrow.com/2019/01/triple-tigers-records-signs-gone-west-for-debut-ep-tides-out-today/|access-date=June 23, 2020|language=en}} The band released their debut and only album, ''Canyons,'' on June 12, 2020. ==Background== ===2018–2019: Formation and debut=== Gone West was formed in 2018 and is composed of Colbie Caillat, Justin Kawika Young, Nelly Joy, and her husband Jason Reeves,{{Cite web|last=Sawyer|first=Bobbie Jean|date=June 12, 2020|title=Gone West Delivers Sun-Soaked Country on Debut Album 'Canyons'|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/gone-west-canyons/|access-date=June 23, 2020|website=Wide Open Country|language=en-US}} and was formed following the four touring together in support of Caillat's ''[[The Malibu Sessions]]''. The band is based out of [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and gets its name from the fact that its four members all hail from states (Reeves from Iowa, Joy from Texas, Caillat from California, and Young from Hawaii) west of Tennessee, which was the inspiration for the band's "autobiographical theme song" and titular track "Gone West."{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8493961/gone-west-colbie-caillat-confetti-premiere|title=Hear 'Confetti,' the Uplifting Track from Colbie Caillat's New Band, Gone West: Premiere|author=Melinda Newman|date=January 17, 2019|magazine=Billboard|accessdate=June 18, 2019}} All of its members had previous experience in the music industry as recording artists and songwriters: Caillat as a Grammy-winning folk pop artist, Young as an artist in the [[Music of Hawaii|contemporary Hawaiian music]] scene, Reeves as a songwriter of some of Caillat's biggest hits and an indie artist, and Nelly Joy as one half of country duo [[the JaneDear girls]]. The EP, ''Tides'', was released on January 18, 2019. It reached No. 7 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Heatseekers Albums chart,{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/heatseekers-albums/2019-02-02 |title=Heatseekers Albums |date=February 2, 2019 |magazine=Billboard }} No. 17 on Country Albums Sales,{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2019-02-02/country-album-sales |title=Country Album Sales |date=February 2, 2019|magazine=Billboard }} and No. 74 on the Top Current Albums chart.{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2019-02-02/current-albums |title=Top Current Albums |date=February 2, 2019|magazine=Billboard }} "[[What Could've Been]]" was released to country radio on July 15, 2019, as the band's debut single and the lead-off single to their debut studio album, ''Canyons'', which was a top 30 hit on the [[Country Airplay]] chart in 2020.{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/colbie-caillat-band-gone-west-single-what-couldve-been-exclusive/|title=Colbie Caillat's Band Gone West Releases New Single 'What Could've Been' — Listen Here! |author=Natalie Stone|date=June 6, 2019|work=People|accessdate=June 18, 2019}}{{Cite magazine|title=Gone West|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/gone-west/chart-history/csa/|access-date=June 23, 2020|magazine=Billboard}} Writing for ''Nashville Lifestyles Magazine'', music critic Luke Levenson praised "What Could've Been," saying it "is a crisp yet plaintive ballad, with vocals which stand out and blend together naturally."{{Cite web|last=Levenson|first=Luke|date=September 3, 2019|title=Gone West|url=https://nashvillelifestyles.com/api/content/e98b35c8-ce69-11e9-9bd9-12f1225286c6/|access-date=July 27, 2020|website=Nashville Lifestyles|language=en-us}} ''Canyons'', Gone West's debut album, was released on June 12, 2020.{{Cite web|last=Franklin|first=Jerrett|date=June 12, 2020|title=Gone West {{!}} "Canyons" - Album Review|url=http://nashvillemusicreviews.com/country/2020/gone-west-canyons-album-review/|access-date=June 23, 2020|website=Nashville Music Reviews|language=en-US}} ===2020–present: Disbandment=== On August 12, 2020, following the split between Caillat and Young, it was announced via social media that the group had disbanded.{{Cite web|url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/gone-west-agonizing-farewell-im-never-getting-over-you/|title=Gone West Bid an Agonizing Farewell in 'I'm Never Getting Over You'|website=Sounds Like Nashville|date=October 2020 |accessdate=January 5, 2022}} ==Discography== ===Studio albums=== {| class="wikitable plainrowheaders" style="text-align:center" |- !
